        <!-- Tab 2: AI Principles -->
        <div id="principles" class="tab-content">
            <h1>AI Principles for Journalists</h1>
            <div class="principles-container">
                
                <div class="principle">
                    <div class="principle-title">Cognitive Load Reduction</div>
                    <div class="principle-content">
                        Think of AI as an intelligent word processor‚Äînot a magic solution, but a tool to reduce cognitive load in strategic places. When you can reduce mental effort in some areas, you free up capacity to either:
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Work smarter and faster</strong> on the same quality of output</li>
                            <li><strong>Go harder in the paint</strong> on the parts that matter most‚Äîdeeper research, better interviews, more thoughtful analysis</li>
                        </ul>
                        The goal isn't to replace your thinking, but to clear space for better thinking.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="principle">
                    <div class="principle-title">There Is No Such Thing as Objectivity</div>
                    <div class="principle-content">
                        We are all subjective beings processing reality through our lived experience. Claiming objectivity as a goal is both impossible and sets you up for false success.
                        <br><br>
                        <strong>Instead, embrace subjectivity consciously:</strong>
                        <ul>
                            <li>The angle you choose affects what story gets told</li>
                            <li>The stakeholders you define and the weight you give them shapes the narrative</li>
                            <li>Curation, editing, and revision are inherently subjective acts</li>
                            <li>Even showing "all perspectives equally" is a strong editorial choice</li>
                        </ul>
                        <strong>Use AI to illuminate these choices:</strong> Ask it to help you see whose perspective is centered, what assumptions you're making, and what voices might be missing. Be aware of your subjective lens, not blind to it.
                        <br><br>
                        <em>Example:</em> In a story about oppression, giving equal weight to oppressor and oppressed perspectives can be misleading. The consequences are not symmetric. Make your choices with awareness, not under the illusion of neutrality.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="principle">
                    <div class="principle-title">Resource Priming</div>
                    <div class="principle-content">
                        Use LLMs to make your reference materials easier to comprehend and navigate. This means:
                        <ul>
                            <li>Converting interviews from audio to searchable text</li>
                            <li>Organizing research notes into structured formats</li>
                            <li>Creating summaries of long documents for quick reference</li>
                            <li>Extracting key themes from multiple sources</li>
                        </ul>
                        The goal is to reduce friction in accessing the information you've gathered, so you can spend more energy on analysis and synthesis.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="principle">
                    <div class="principle-title">You Are in the Driver's Seat</div>
                    <div class="principle-content">
                        Think of AI as an intelligent word processor, not an ultimate source of truth. <strong>You decide when, how, and if to use these tools.</strong>
                        <br><br>
                        <strong>Expect mistakes.</strong> AI will get things wrong. Your discernment is critical. The more seamless your integration of judgment with the tool, the less time you'll spend in "AI Purgatory"‚Äîthat frustrating place where you're spending more time going back and forth with AI than it would take to just do it yourself.
                        <br><br>
                        <strong>Some things should take time.</strong> Not everything needs to be faster. Allow work that deserves depth to take the time it needs. You're absolutely in control here.
                        <br><br>
                        Be aware of how your colleagues and fellow journalists are using AI, and operate accordingly. Let your discernment guide every interaction.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="principle">
                    <div class="principle-title">Natural Language Replaces Keyword Search</div>
                    <div class="principle-content">
                        We grew up in the age where advanced keyword search was a crucial skill‚Äîknowing how to craft the right Google query, click through multiple links, and connect dots across sources.
                        <br><br>
                        <strong>LLMs change this.</strong> For about 80% of inquiries, you can now use natural language instead of keyword gymnastics.
                        <br><br>
                        <em>Example:</em> Previously, "I want to understand how a city budget works in context" would require multiple Google sessions, link-clicking, and significant time connecting dots. Now, you can just ask that question directly and get contextual understanding much faster.
                        <br><br>
                        This represents a significant reduction in our collective cognitive load‚Äîfreeing up mental energy for deeper analysis and synthesis.
                    </div>
                </div>

            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Tab 3: AI Skills Reference -->
        <div id="skills" class="tab-content">
            <h1>AI Skills Quick Reference</h1>
            <div class="skills-container">

                <div class="skill-card">
                    <div class="skill-stage">Stage 2: Fuzzy Idea / Initial Spark</div>
                    <div class="skill-name">Voice-to-Text Conversation & Initial Gap Analysis</div>
                    <div class="skill-detail">
                        Use speech-to-text tools to have a conversation with an AI, dumping your jumbled thoughts. Then use an LLM to organize and clarify your thinking, and identify gaps in your initial concept.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="skill-card">
                    <div class="skill-stage">Stage 4: Research, Angle Discovery & Stakeholder Consideration</div>
                    <div class="skill-name">Gap Analysis (Post-Angle)</div>
                    <div class="skill-detail">
                        After choosing your angle, ask AI: "What gaps exist in my research? What perspectives am I missing? What questions haven't I asked?" This reveals blind spots in your chosen approach.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="skill-card">
                    <div class="skill-stage">Stage 6: Interviewing & Primary Reporting</div>
                    <div class="skill-name">Resource Priming (Interview Transcription)</div>
                    <div class="skill-detail">
                        Convert interview recordings to searchable text using transcription tools. Makes it much easier to reference specific quotes and identify themes across multiple conversations.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="skill-card">
                    <div class="skill-stage">Stage 7: Outline</div>
                    <div class="skill-name">Outline Check / Bias Interrogation</div>
                    <div class="skill-detail">
                        Ask AI: "Based on this outline, what will readers assume my bias is? Whose story is getting told?" Examines your subjective choices in structure and emphasis before drafting.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="skill-card">
                    <div class="skill-stage">Stage 8: Draft</div>
                    <div class="skill-name">Claim and Assumption Categorization</div>
                    <div class="skill-detail">
                        Request a claim identification analysis from AI. Have it identify: What claims are you making? What assumptions underlie them? What perspective is centered? What weight is given to different stakeholders?
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="skill-card">
                    <div class="skill-stage">Stages 1, 3, 4: Throughout Research Process</div>
                    <div class="skill-name">Natural Language Search</div>
                    <div class="skill-detail">
                        Ask questions conversationally instead of crafting keyword searches. Example: "How does a city budget work in context?" instead of multiple Google sessions. Works for ~80% of inquiries and dramatically reduces cognitive load.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="skill-card">
                    <div class="skill-stage">Stages 7, 8, 12: Outline, Draft, Publish Prep</div>
                    <div class="skill-name">HTML/CSS Visual Reference Generation</div>
                    <div class="skill-detail">
                        NOT AI image generation. Have AI create HTML/CSS mockups of timelines, visualizations, or infographics based on your copy. Use these as reference images in Canva or other design tools. Reduces 3+ hour design work to under 90 minutes by giving you a visual starting point to revise from.
                    </div>
                </div>

            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Tab 4: AI Mishaps -->
        <div id="mishaps" class="tab-content">
            <h1>AI Mishaps to Watch For</h1>
            <div class="mishaps-container">

                <div class="mishap-card">
                    <div class="mishap-icon">‚ö†Ô∏è</div>
                    <div class="mishap-name">AI Off the Rails / Incorrect Information</div>
                    <div class="mishap-description">
                        When AI repeatedly gives you incorrect information or makes claims that don't align with your sources, it's not being malicious‚Äîit's working with limited or incorrect training data.
                        <br><br>
                        Think of it like talking to a genius who doesn't know everything. They can take limited initial information and create something that's logically consistent and sounds convincing, but may be factually wrong. The AI can run with incomplete data and produce outputs that make logical sense without being true.
                    </div>
                    <div class="mishap-solution">
                        <strong>Solution:</strong> When you find yourself correcting AI repeatedly, that's a signal. You need to feed it better primary data‚Äîinterviews, verified sources, original documents, or research. The problem isn't the AI; it's that the information it was trained on for this specific topic is inadequate or incorrect.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="mishap-card">
                    <div class="mishap-icon">üîÑ</div>
                    <div class="mishap-name">AI Purgatory</div>
                    <div class="mishap-description">
                        You've spent more time going back and forth with AI than it would have taken to do the task yourself. You're stuck in endless iterations, refinements, and re-prompting without making real progress.
                        <br><br>
                        This happens when there's a mismatch between your discernment, the tool's capabilities, and your end goal. It's frustrating, time-consuming, and counterproductive.
                    </div>
                    <div class="mishap-solution">
                        <strong>Solution:</strong> Step back. Ask yourself:
                        <ul style="margin-top: 10px;">
                            <li>Am I providing clear enough prompts and context?</li>
                            <li>Does this task actually benefit from AI assistance?</li>
                            <li>Would it be faster to just do this myself?</li>
                        </ul>
                        The goal is seamless integration of your discernment with the tool. If you're spending excessive time iterating, either refine your approach or abandon AI for this particular task. You're in the driver's seat‚Äîdon't be afraid to take back the wheel.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="mishap-card">
                    <div class="mishap-icon">üéØ</div>
                    <div class="mishap-name">Treating AI as Ultimate Truth</div>
                    <div class="mishap-description">
                        Accepting AI outputs as fact without verification. Assuming that because AI sounds confident, it must be correct. Forgetting that AI is a tool, not a journalist.
                        <br><br>
                        Remember: There is no ultimate source of truth. The act of journalism is understanding that any one story is actually 20 stories‚Äîthe one being told, the one being minimized, the one intentionally left out.
                    </div>
                    <div class="mishap-solution">
                        <strong>Solution:</strong> Think of AI as an intelligent word processor, not an oracle. Use your discernment, verify claims against primary sources, and remember that your editorial judgment is irreplaceable. AI can help you work smarter, but it can't replace the critical thinking and ethical considerations that define good journalism.
                    </div>
                </div>

            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Tab 5: Overview -->
        <div id="overview" class="tab-content">
